---
// Beyond reclassification: Steps 8-11
---
<section class="px-6 pb-16 border-t border-white/5">
  <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto">
    <!-- Part B header -->
    <div class="mt-12 mb-8">
      <span class="text-[10px] uppercase tracking-widest text-neutral-500 font-semibold">Beyond reclassification</span>
      <h3 class="text-base font-bold mt-1">I couldn't stop there</h3>
      <p class="text-xs text-neutral-400 mt-2 max-w-2xl leading-relaxed">
        Once I understood how to read protein structures, I realized I could go further. 
        I'm not a geneticist, but these tools exist, they're free, and my son's future might depend on someone asking the right questions. 
        So I kept going.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="space-y-6 mb-8">
      <!-- Step 8 -->
      <div class="bg-white/[0.02] border border-white/5 rounded-lg p-5">
        <div class="flex items-center gap-2 mb-3">
          <span class="w-7 h-7 rounded-full bg-purple-500/20 flex items-center justify-center text-xs font-bold text-purple-400 shrink-0">8</span>
          <h3 class="text-sm font-semibold">I checked if CRISPR could fix the mutation directly</h3>
        </div>
        <p class="text-xs text-neutral-400 leading-relaxed mb-3">
          Instead of replacing the whole gene, what if we could fix just the one wrong letter? 
          I downloaded the genomic sequence around Michael's variant from 
          <a href="https://rest.ensembl.org" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Ensembl</a> 
          and checked whether gene editing tools could target it.
        </p>
        <p class="text-xs text-neutral-300 leading-relaxed">
          <strong>Base editing (CBE/ABE): cannot fix this variant</strong> (C>A transversion is outside their range).
          <strong>Prime editing: feasible.</strong> I found a suitable PAM site just 4 base pairs from the mutation. 
          A prime editor could theoretically correct the single base change, though this approach has not yet been tested in inner ear cells.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- Step 9 -->
      <div class="bg-white/[0.02] border border-white/5 rounded-lg p-5">
        <div class="flex items-center gap-2 mb-3">
          <span class="w-7 h-7 rounded-full bg-purple-500/20 flex items-center justify-center text-xs font-bold text-purple-400 shrink-0">9</span>
          <h3 class="text-sm font-semibold">I asked: can the gene fit in a single virus?</h3>
        </div>
        <p class="text-xs text-neutral-400 leading-relaxed mb-3">
          Current gene therapy for STRC requires two viruses (dual-AAV) because the gene is too long for one. 
          Two viruses means lower efficiency: both must enter the same cell.
          I analyzed the AlphaFold structure and noticed that the first ~600 amino acids have very low structural confidence (pLDDT below 50), 
          suggesting they may not form a stable structure and might be dispensable.
        </p>
        <p class="text-xs text-neutral-300 leading-relaxed">
          <strong>If those regions are removed, the remaining "mini-stereocilin" (1328 aa, 3984 bp) fits in a single AAV vector.</strong> 
          This is a computational hypothesis. It needs lab testing. But the precedent exists: 
          micro-dystrophin (removing non-essential parts of dystrophin) is now in Phase 3 clinical trials for muscular dystrophy.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- Step 10 -->
      <div class="bg-white/[0.02] border border-white/5 rounded-lg p-5">
        <div class="flex items-center gap-2 mb-3">
          <span class="w-7 h-7 rounded-full bg-purple-500/20 flex items-center justify-center text-xs font-bold text-purple-400 shrink-0">10</span>
          <h3 class="text-sm font-semibold">I predicted the protein-protein interaction (AlphaFold 3)</h3>
        </div>
        <p class="text-xs text-neutral-400 leading-relaxed mb-3">
          To test the mini-STRC idea further, I submitted a job to 
          <a href="https://alphafoldserver.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener">AlphaFold 3 Server</a> 
          to predict the 3D structure of stereocilin bound to its interaction partner TMEM145 
          (a protein recently discovered to be essential for stereocilin's function, Nature Communications 2025).
        </p>
        <p class="text-xs text-neutral-300 leading-relaxed mb-3">
          <strong>Results received.</strong> ipTM = 0.47, pTM = 0.48. AlphaFold 3 shows <strong>low confidence</strong> 
          in a direct STRC-TMEM145 dimer interaction (ipTM > 0.8 would indicate confident binding).
        </p>
        <p class="text-xs text-neutral-400 leading-relaxed">
          This likely means the two proteins don't interact as a simple pair. They may require additional partners, 
          or their interaction may be membrane-dependent (TMEM145 is a transmembrane protein). For the mini-STRC hypothesis, 
          this is a neutral result: the N-terminal region is not predicted to be at an interaction interface, 
          but neither is any other region with high confidence.
        </p>
        <div class="mt-3 text-xs text-neutral-500 bg-black/30 p-3 rounded">
          <a href="https://alphafoldserver.com/fold/739cbeb76239c7c8" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="text-blue-400">View full AlphaFold 3 results</a> (requires Google login)
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Step 11 -->
      <div class="bg-white/[0.02] border border-blue-500/10 rounded-lg p-5">
        <div class="flex items-center gap-2 mb-3">
          <span class="w-7 h-7 rounded-full bg-blue-500/20 flex items-center justify-center text-xs font-bold text-blue-400 shrink-0">11</span>
          <h3 class="text-sm font-semibold">I wrote to the researchers</h3>
        </div>
        <p class="text-xs text-neutral-400 leading-relaxed mb-3">
          I emailed the leading researchers working on STRC gene therapy at institutions in the US, France, and China. 
          I shared the reclassification evidence, the mini-STRC hypothesis, and a link to this website.
        </p>
        <p class="text-xs text-neutral-300 leading-relaxed">
          I received encouraging responses confirming the computational approach is sound 
          and that the analysis has been shared with research teams working on STRC gene therapy.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>
